##How do large multinational advertising groups get to work as the epidemic spreads across the globe?

Function introduction, the interface news is China has the influence original financial and economic new media, only serves the independent thinking crowd

REPORTER: Editor Ma Yue: Ya Han Xiang

“

Several advertising companies confirmed to interface news that telecommuting is the new normal and that most business travel to and from China, Japan, Iran, South Korea and northern Italy is banned.

”

“

Several advertising companies confirmed to interface news that telecommuting is the new normal and that most business travel to and from China, Japan, Iran, South Korea and northern Italy is banned.

”

As of 17:00 GMT, 2 March, the number of new cases outside China was almost nine times higher than in China, according to the World Health Organization (WHO) , has spread to every continent except Antarctica. The cumulative number of cases outside China exceeded. million.

Large multinational advertising groups have responded to the outbreak by working remotely, restricting travel to affected countries and regions, and a handful of companies have temporarily closed their offices.

Tokyo-based dentsu-angis Group has attracted much attention, with 276 confirmed cases in Japan as of March 3(plus 706 confirmed by Diamond Princess) . A 50-year-old male employee at Dentsu's Tokyo headquarters was diagnosed Tuesday, Bloomberg reported.

With the epidemic in China under control and the overall resumption of production, Anguix told interface that all offices in China have now been opened except for Wuhan. The group arranged for its employees to start working remotely from February 10, and to shift from peak to office from February 24. The head of Department may assign no more than 50% of the returning office staff to return to the office based on actual business needs, subject to prior application and approval by the CEO of the brand, the rest of my colleagues continue to work from home.

In response to the recent outbreak spreading to more countries and regions, Anguix stressed in the latest travel guide policy issued to employees that all business travel must be approved in advance by the group CEO. The list of restricted travel destinations will be updated as circumstances change.

Currently, until further notice, Dentsu Anguix does not allow business travel between Taegu and Cheongdo County, Lombardy and Veneto in northern Italy, Iran and its Tokyo headquarters (Shiodome) . If an employee has recently returned from any of these locations (whether for business or personal travel) , he must notify his department manager and local head of human resources and isolate himself or herself for 14 days.

Interpublic Group has restricted all business travel between China and South Korea until further notice. According to Adweek, any employee who has recently visited mainland China, South Korea or Italy must work from home for 14 days, employees who have had close contact with people who have travelled to the above-mentioned locations are also required to work from home for 14 days. The company is working closely with medical consultants to monitor market conditions and adjust working arrangements to ensure the safety of its employees, a spokeswoman said. Work is also being done with technical departments to respond to possible extension of Home Office hours.

According to Adweek, the Omnicom Group implemented travel rules for employees on Feb. 26, this includes postponing all business trips to and from mainland China, Japan, Hong Kong, Iran, Singapore, South Korea, Thailand, Taiwan and northern Italy until further notice. Employees returning from these countries or regions will also be quarantined at home for 14 days.

The BBDO Beijing Office of Omnicom Group confirmed the rule to interface news, adding that Greater China has asked to cancel all travel since the outbreak began, and has also set up an emergency team for the outbreak, weekly updates on the situation will be issued in response. At present, Beijing and Shanghai offices have adopted a staggered shift arrangement.

Havas Group has suspended business travel to and from "high-risk exposed areas" until further notice. So far, these include Greater China, Singapore, South Korea and the Italian regions of Lombardy and Veneto.

In addition, anyone travelling on business, personal travel or stopovers from these areas must be quarantined for 14 days upon return. The workers can work from home or take time off, Hawass said.

WPP's Ogilvy & Mather China told interface that Beijing offices will resume telecommuting from Feb. 3, while Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenzhen will resume telecommuting from Feb. 10, depending on local government policies. Offices in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenzhen have resumed normal operations since Feb. 17, but employees are encouraged to work from home, depending on work conditions.

Staff going to Ogilvy's office must have completed a 14-day home health observation at their place of work. Staff are required to report and apply for admission to the office the day before, so that the company can keep track of the people in the office. Employees are advised to stay in the office for no more than 6 hours per day and to leave the office by 7 pm.

Ogilvy China, meanwhile, has essentially stopped all travel, but any urgently needed trips must be approved by the head of each office.
